ecce Volcanus. Volcanus est deus laboris.

sed Volcanus est deus foedus quem mater non amat.
itaque Iuno filium ex Olympo iacit.
Volcanus totam diem per aerem cadit.
deinde Volcanus in mare cadit.
ecce Thetis. Thetis est dea maris.
Thetis Volcanum sub mare videt et eum iuvat.
Thetis et sorores Volcanum curant.
et Volcanus dona sororibus facit.
olim Volcanus sellam insidiosam facit.
Volcanus sellam insidiosam ad matrem misit.
Iuno statim in sellam insidiosam sedet.
eheu! sella Iunonem captat.
diu Iuno in sella captiva est.
nam nemo Iunonem liberare potest.
nisi Volcanus.
ecce Mars. Mars est deus belli.
Mars Volcanum visitat.
‘libera Iunonem!’ Mars iubet.
sed Volcanus negat.
ecce Bacchus. Bacchus est deus vini.
Bacchus quoque Volcanum visitat.
‘libera Iunonem!’ Bacchus quoque iubet.
sed Volcanus iterum negat.
tum Bacchus multum vinum Volcano dat.
mox Volcanus ebrius est.
Bacchus Volcanum ebrium ad Olympum ducit.
‘libera me!’ Iuno clamat.
ecce Venus. Venus est dea pulcritudinis et amoris.
Volcanus Venerem videt. Volcanus Venerem desiderat.
‘ego te liberabo, si tu mihi Venerem dabis,’ Volcanus dicit.
Iuno Venerem Volcano promittit. Volcanus Iunonem liberat.
Iuno Baccho multas gratias agit.
nunc Bacchus laetus est. nunc Iuno laeta est. nunc Volcanus laetus est.
sed Venus non est laeta.
nam Venus non Volcanum sed Martem amat.

The world is not as big as we think.  We are connected to many countries. This is called globalization.
Globalization is a word that explains the exchange of people, culture, goods and ideas.
Many items we use in America are made in different countries, like China.
BMWs are designed in Germany, built in several countries and then sold to people in America.
Even American flags are made in other countries. Since we buy goods from those countries, we connect with them.
McDonald's is from America but they have restaurants in every part of the world.
In America, we eat food from other countries, like Mexico.  We exchanged culture with Mexico.  This is globalization.
This Dutch family lives in America and is playing croquet, a sport from England.  This is an exchange of people and culture.
Even though our world may seem big, globalization shows that it is not as big as we think.

Cesar Chavez was a Mexican American labor leader and civil rights worker.
He worked to improve the conditions for farm workers in America.
He was born near Yuma, Arizona on March 31, 1927.
His family owned their own farm until they lost it in the Great Depression.
When Cesar was 11, the family moved to California and became migrant farm workers.
Everyone worked long, hard hours every day, including Cesar.
Most workers were treated very badly and given no clean water or bathrooms.
Migrant farm workers were very poor.
When he grew up, Cesar began to help the migrant farm workers in California.
He used peaceful ways like speeches, marches, boycotts, and strikes.
In a boycott, people refuse to buy things from a company that doesn't treat its workers fairly.
In a strike, workers refuse to work until they are treated fairly or paid higher wages.
Cesar helped people learn to work together to get the respect they deserved.
He formed the National Farm Workers Association with another labor leader.
This union later became United Farm Workers. It helped many people.
One strike by grape pickers lasted for 5 years, and the workers won. They got higher pay.
For 30 years, Cesar Chavez worked to get better pay and working conditions for America's poorest workers.
He helped workers in California, Texas, Arizona, and Florida.
As he got older, he began to work against the use of pesticides on farms.
Pesticides are chemicals that are used to kill pests that can harm plants.
He told people that pesticides could harm farm workers and their children.
One way he got attention for his causes was to go on hunger strikes.
During a hunger strike, a person does not eat any food.
During one hunger strike, Cesar did not eat for 36 days!
Chavez died on April 23, 1993.
After he died, he was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom.
In 2000, California established a state holiday to be held on his birthday.
Thanks to Cesar Chavez, conditions for farm workers in America are better.
Thank you, Cesar Chavez!

Go to the supermarket and buy the necessary ingredients for your pizza:
Olive oil,
corn meal,
flour,
tomato sauce,
mozzarella and parmesan cheese,
oregano,
sliced ham (optional),
tuna (optional),
pepperoni (optional),
sliced mushrooms (optional),
still water,
and salt.
Once you have all the ingredients ready, you need to prepare the dough.
You can buy one at the supermarket or...
You can prepare a homemade one!
First step: Put hot water in a pan and add yeast. Stir and let sit for 5 to 10 minutes. Then, add salt and oil.
Second step: Add flour and wait until the mixture is thick enough.
Third step: Let rise up for 1 hour at room temperature and 5 hours in the refrigerator.
Fourth step:Cut the dough into two round balls and make the desired shape with your hands.
To sum up, these images show how to prepare pizza dough.
After that, spread the tomato sauce on the dough and put the cheese on the top.
Add the ingredients that you have chosen for your pizza: ham, mushrooms, tuna or pepperoni.
Introduce the pizza into the oven at 175º to 250º approximately
Remember! These are all the steps to cook pizza.

The Holocaust
The Holocaust was a terrible time when many people were killed.  These were people that didn't do anything wrong.
There were about 10 million men, women and children that died in the Holocaust. This photo has one million people in it.
A lot of the people that were killed in the Holocaust were Jewish.  They have their own religion, language, & culture.
This is the symbol some people had to wear during the Holocaust, so that everyone knew they were Jewish.
Other people that were killed had disabilities, or were Romani.
The bosses of the Holocaust thought they should get rid of people that were different.
The people killed in the Holocaust were first sent to concentration camps.  It was really bad there.
There was almost no food, bad houses, and lots of sickness with no medicine.  It was like a terrible jail.
There were lots of concentration camps in Europe.  This is a map of all the places where people were locked up.
Sometimes you would have a tattoo on your body if you were in a concentration camp.
Sometimes families were separated.  Children missed their family and were very sad.
Famous people like Anne Frank were victims of the Holocaust.  Anne wrote all about hiding in her diary.
She was hiding to stay out of a concentration camp.  She was killed for being Jewish when she was a teenager.
The Holocaust was one of the reasons for World War II.  People from all over the world fought really hard for a long time.
There were bombs and soldiers in lots of places in Europe.  There were airplanes and tanks.

The broth grew cloudy.

title: Jack and Annie and the Talking Doll

pages.caption: One summer day, Jack and Annie were making a doll in the tree house .
The doll that Annie was making suddenly started to speak. "Hi," said the doll.
Annie screamed, "Ahhh!"
Then Annie turned around and found a cash register.
Jack walked over to the table.
The doll said, "Jack look inside for money."
Jack and Annie went home to tell their Mom and Dad.

Merlin was waiting for Jack and Annie. "Hi," said Jack and Annie .
Merlin said, "Now, pay me the money for the doll."
Merlin went home. Jack and Annie took the doll home. The End.
The sun is Earth's closest star. It's the center of our solar system. It supports life on Earth.
The sun is a Yellow Dwarf Star. It is made of burning gasses. The gasses are hydrogen and helium.
The sun is a sphere shape. The surface is called the photosphere. The photosphere is 10,000° Fahrenheit.
The sun's core is even hotter. It can reach almost 30 million° Fahrenheit.
The sun is about 870,000 miles wide. It's larger than any of the planets. Thousands of Earths could fit inside!
All the planets orbit the sun. The sun is spinning in place. One full rotation takes about 30 days.
Earth's orbit around the sun takes 365 days. Earth is also spinning in place. One full rotation takes 24 hours.
The moon doesn't make light. The sun shines onto the moon. It gives the moon its brightness.
The sun causes weather on Earth. It warms Earth's surface. Water evaporates and later becomes rainfall.
The sun causes seasons on Earth. Seasons change as Earth orbits the sun.
The sun is 4.5 billion years old. It will likely burn for billions more.

title: The Giver: The Giver's Favorite Memory

pages.caption: Jonas finds the Giver in incredible pain!
The Giver asks, "Can you take some of my pain away?"
The Giver transmits a terrible memory of a battlefield filled with dying men.
Jonas is horribly wounded.
He gives water to a young soldier, but then watches him die.
After this memory, Jonas never wants to return to the Giver's apartment.
When he does, the Giver transmits beautiful memories to Jonas.
He transmits memories of birthday parties, museums, and camping.
Jonas asks, "Of all the memories you have, which is your favorite?"
The Giver gives a memory of a family - including children, parents, and grandparents - opening presents at Christmas.
Jonas has never heard of grandparents.
In Jonas's community, parents are not part of their children's lives once the children have grown.
Jonas asks, "What was the feeling in the Christmas room?" The Giver replies, "That was love."
Jonas says, "I wish my family could be more like that and that you could be my grandfather!"
Later that evening, Jonas asks his parents, "Do you love me?"
His parents laugh and tell him to be more precise in his word choice - the word "love" is too general!
Jonas is confused. Why can his parents not say they love him?
That night, Jonas tells Gabriel about colors, grandparents, and love. Gabriel can only sleep when Jonas gives him memories.
The next day, Jonas decides to stop taking his morning pill.

title: Captain James Cook: The Early Years

pages.caption: James Cook was born in 1728.
He was born in England. He grew up on a farm.  He went to school in the local village.
When he was 17 he started working in a shop. He didn’t like it!
When he was 19 he went to work on a ship. He was an apprentice. For three years he learned about ships.
He also learned mathematics. He learned how to steer the ship using the stars as a map.
Then he got a job on a ship. For two years he worked on a ship to Europe.
The ship took coal to different places to sell.
After two years he went to work for the navy. He worked for another two years on a ship going to Europe.
Two years later he sailed to Canada. He was 30 years old.
He went to fight in a war. The war was against the French.
After the war he began to make maps in Canada.
He worked hard to make a map of Newfoundland in the summer.
He went back to England in the winter. He read lots of books. He wanted to learn more about making maps.
When he was 33 he went to England for the winter. This year he got married. His wife was named Elizabeth.
Three years later he finished the map of Newfoundland. People really liked his map.
Lots of people wanted him to make more maps.
They asked him to travel more.
They wanted him to explore and find new countries.
To find out more read "Captain James Cook: Explorer"

The elephant's natural home is in the tropics of Africa and Asia.
They use their tusks to dig for food and move branches. Sometimes they are used as weapons.
Trunks are used for gathering food, drinking, washing, smelling and talking to each other.
African elephants can weigh up to 7,000 kilograms.
Elephants use their tails to swat away flies and other insects.
Elephants have quite poor eyesight so they rely on their excellent sense of hearing and smell.
Elephants live in family groups. They share the responsibility of raising and protecting babies.
The calf suckles with its mouth, not its trunk. They weigh up to 110 kilograms and drink up to 12 litres of milk a day.
Adults can sleep standing up if danger comes too near. The females flap and trumpet in a frightening way.
All the elephants have had plenty to drink and have bathed.
Big elephants can reach 6 or 7 metres (20 to 23 ft) into the air with their trunks when they rear up on their hind legs.
An African Elephant's ears are about three times size of Asian Elephants.
Elephants have thick tough skin. But you wouldn't think that they have very sensitive skin and need to find shade.
I like Elephants.
The King asked the Queen,
and The Queen asked The Dairymaid:
"Could we have some butter for The Royal slice of bread?"
The Queen asked The Dairymaid, the Dairymaid said,
"Certainly, I'll go and tell the cow now, before she goes to bed."
The Dairymaid, she curtsied, and went and told The Cow:
"Don't forget the butter for the royal slice of bread."
The Cow said sleepily:
"You'd better tell His Majesty that many people nowadays like marmalade instead."
The Dairymaid said, "Fancy!"
And went to Her Majesty.
She curtsied to the Queen, and she turned a little red:
"Excuse me, Your Majesty, for taking of the liberty, but marmalade is tasty, if it's very thickly spread."
The Queen said "Oh!" and went to His Majesty:
"Talking of the butter for The Royal slice of bread, many people think that marmalade is nicer.
Would you like to try a little Marmalade instead?"
The King said, "Bother!" And then he said, "Oh, dear me!"
The King sobbed, "Oh, deary me!" and went back to bed.
"Nobody," he whimpered, "Could call me a fussy man; I only want a little bit of butter for my bread!"
The Queen said "There, there!" and went to The Dairymaid.
The Dairymaid said, "There, there!" And went to the shed.
The Cow said, "There, there! I didn't really mean it;
Here's milk for his porringer and butter for his bread."
The Queen took the butter and brought it to His Majesty;
The King said, "Butter, eh?" And bounced out of bed.
"Nobody," he said, as he kissed her tenderly,
"Nobody," he said, as he slid down the banisters,
"Nobody, My darling, Could call me a fussy man - BUT
I do like a little bit of butter to my bread!"

The next day, Jonas asks the Giver, "Do you think about release?"
He says, "I think about my own release when I am in pain, but I cannot apply for release until I train you."
Jonas cannot ask for release either. This rule was created after the failure of the new Receiver ten years ago.
Jonas asks, "What happened?" He asks over and over again.
The Giver says, "The failed Receiver was intelligent and eager to learn. Her name was Rosemary."
The Giver says, "I loved her, and I love you in the same way."
At first, the Giver gave Rosemary happy memories to make her laugh during her training.
The Giver could not bring himself to give Rosemary memories of physical pain.
At her request, the Giver gave Rosemary memories of loneliness, loss, poverty, and fear.
After a very hard session, Rosemary kissed the Giver's cheek and left. She never came back again.
Later, the Giver learned that she had applied for release that day.
Jonas says, "I know I cannot apply for release, but what would happen to all the memories if I drowned in the river?"
The Giver says, "It would be a disaster!"
He says, "The memories would not be lost. They would go to all the people in the community!"
The community would be overwhelmed by the memories.
The Giver tells Jonas, "Stay away from the river, just in case!"

title: The Giver: The True Meaning of Release

pages.caption: Jonas tells the Giver, "I am curious about release because my father released a new child today."
The Giver says, "I wish new children were not released."
Jonas reminds the Giver of how confusing it would be to have two identical people in the community!
The Giver tells Jonas, "Because you are the Receiver, you can access any information you want. You can watch a release."
Since all private ceremonies are recorded, Jonas can even watch his father's release of the new child from  this morning.
Jonas agrees to watch, and the Giver calls up the recording on a video screen.
Jonas watches his father weigh the twins and inject something into the head of the smaller new child.
The new child twitches and lies still. Jonas knows that it is now dead.
He knows this because the new child moves in the same way as the boy he watched die on the battlefield.
Horrified, Jonas watches his father place the body in a garbage chute and wave goodbye.
The Giver says, "I watched Rosemary's release. She was told to roll up her sleeve, but she chose to inject herself."

title: How to Make Rice Krispie treats

pages.caption: How to Make Rice Krispie Treats
Ingredients
6 cups of Rice Krispies Cereal
3 tablespoons of butter
4 cups of mini-marshmallows
Lightly spray non-stick cooking spray into your pan.
Cooking Spray
Gather all the ingredients
Get a small bowl and microwave the butter for 10 seconds.
Get a large bowl and melt the marshmallows for 30 seconds at a time.
Pour the melted butter into the melted marshmallows. Stir.
Pour the Rice Krispies into the mixture one cup at a time. Stir.
Transfer the Rice Krispie mixture into the pan and mix evenly.
Place pan in the refrigerator for 20-30 minutes to harden.
Cut Rice Krispie treats with cookie cutters.
Eat!
The End.

Television has lots of important roles, such as teaching, informing, communicating and sharing.
In the 1800s many different inventors worked on different types of televisions.
It is not known exactly who invented the very first television, as lots of people experimented with ideas.
It was at the World Fair in Paris in 1900 that the word "television" was first used.
The first televisions had no sound.
After World War 1, inventors of the radio wanted to combine pictures with sound.
In 1928 television channels were first shown in the United States, and the first television was sold.
The first televisions were very small, with only black and white pictures.
Watching television was something the whole family did together, as televisions were expensive and families only had one.
Televisions slowly grew bigger and cheaper.
In 1950 colour television was first released in the United States.
Colour television arrived in Australia in time for the 1956 Olympics in Melbourne.
The first landing on the moon in 1969 was shown on television, and was the first major world event to be on television.
Through the 1970s and 1980s more people had televisions in their houses, with some houses having two!
The flat screen television became popular in the late 1990s.
By 2000 nearly every house in the western world had a television.
Now televisions are used not only for watching, but to connect to the internet, play games and talk to people.

Los geniecillos holgazanes
Érase unos duendecillos que vivían en un lindo bosque.
Su casita pudo haber sido un primor, si se hubieran ocupado de limpiarla
Pero como eran tan holgazanes la suciedad la hacía inhabitable.
Un día se les apareció la Reina de las hadas y les dijo:

- Voy a mandaros a la bruja gruñona para que cuide de vuestra casa.
Desde luego, no os resultará simpática...
y llegó la Bruja Gruñona montada en su escoba.
Llevaba seis pares de gafas para ver mejor las motas de polvo y empezó a escobazos con todos.
Los geniecillos aburridos de tener que limpiar fueron a ver a un mago amigo
para que les transformase en pájaros. Y así, batiendo sus alas, se fueron muy lejos...
En los sucesivo pasaron hambre y frío;
a merced de los elementos y sin casa donde cobijarse, recordaban con pena su acogedora morada del bosque.
Bien castigados estaban por su holgazanería, errando siempre por el espacio...
Jamás volvieron a disfrutar de su casita del bosque que fue habitada por otros geniecillos más obedientes y trabajadores.

La Granja Tesorito se fundó en los años 70 por diferentes profesores de la Universidad de Caldas, entre ellos Gerardo Téllez.
En la Granja se hacen cultivos de hongos, los que crecen a partir de una cepa madre. La cepa se cultiva en un medio especial.

Pendant ces vacances de Noël on voulait faire quelque chose de différent
et nous nous sommes réunis pour prendre note de nos idées et les mettre en commun.
On a commencé par faire une collecte de vêtements pour les plus démunis,
et par rassembler tous nos jouets pour les envoyer aux enfants plus pauvres que nous.
Un groupe de la 3ème année a eu l´idée de faire une pièce de théâtre
pour la représenter dans la place du village et acheter des aliments pour les familles sans travail
avec la vente des entrées. L´idée a eu un grand succès et la salle de théâtre était bondée
le jour de la représentation. Avec l´argent obtenu on a acheté aussi des emballages pour les jouets
et on a aussi élaboré des cartes postales pour les vendre et augmenter notre budget solidaire.
Tout le monde a collaboré à cette iniciative, même les adultes,
et on a appris que les vacances de Noël et la semaine avant ces vacances-là,
pouvaient etre plus amusantes que d´habitude. On a  bien rigolé ensemble en faisant ces activités-là.
La semaine avant Noël on a décidé en plus, de lire des livres aux vieillards qui vivaient seuls, sans famille,
et on a aussi élaboré des gâteaux à la maison pour ces gens-là,
comme notre cadeau de Noël pour eux. On a demandé des recettes à nos mères
et on a appris des tas et des tas de choses. Avec les restes des biscuits qui ne servaient pas
pour former des figurines de Noël on a fait un petit gueuleton pour nous tous ensemble.
Pour compléter notre programme on a décidé aussi d´être plus actifs cette année-là à la maison
et d´aider nos mères avec les préparatifs  de Noël pour la famille
afin de leur éviter ou diminuer  le stress typique de ces dates.
Vraiement, l´expérience a été très intéressante et on a décidé que la prochaine année
on ferait quelque chose de similaire et de gratifiant pour rendre nos vacances inoubliables et solidaires.

title: La historia de Pablo y su perro Canelo

pages.caption: Pablo era un niño de 8 años que vivía en el campo con su familia y su adorable perro Canelo.
Canelo era un perro precioso, de color marrón y hocico negro. Para Pablo era  toda su vida.
Todas las tardes iban a pasear juntos recorriendo los alrededores del pueblo.
Pablo le prometió que siempre estarían juntos y Canelo siempre le respondía con una caricia.
Pero pasaron los años y Pablo tuvo que irse a la ciudad a realizar sus estudios.
Canelo se quedó muy triste. Ya no era ese perro juguetón que corría sin parar.
Un verano su padre le llamó para decirle que Canelo había envejecido y estaba enfermo.
Pablo  fue a ver a su adorable Canelo. Cuando lo vió se puso a llorar y  recordó su infancia junto a él.
Decidió cuidarlo y pasar el máximo tiempo posible con él, como hacía en su infancia. Corrían juntos por  la playa.
Incluso lo llevaba al fútbol. De nuevo ese vínculo de amistad volvía a estar presente entre ellos.

Early American Houses
Long ago early Americans lived in many kinds of houses. They used what was close to them.
Woodland Indians lived where there were many trees.
They used tree bark and wood to make their houses.
Wigwams were small houses made of tree bark and sticks.
Some Woodland Indians made long houses. They were bigger than wigwams.
Plains Indians lived where there were only a few trees but lots of grass.
There were many buffalo where the Plains Indians lived.
They used buffalo skins to make houses called tepees.
This woman is sitting outside of her tepee.
Southwestern Indians lived where there was very little water. It was hot and dry.
They made houses out of clay. These are called adobe houses.
Adobe houses kept the people cool when it was hot outside.
If you wanted to build a house, what would you use?

In 1971, a solo career was launched.

By far, he was nominated for thirteen Grammys.
MJ was also famous for doing the moonwalk. He unveiled it in 1983. It became his signature move.
On June 25th, 2009, MJ died after suffering cardiac arrest from an overdose of propofol.

A long, long time ago, two groups of people lived in America. These were Native Americans and Colonial Americans.
How were the Native Americans and the Colonial Americans different?
Native Americans lived in tribes. A tribe is a group of people who live together mainly because they are related.

Native Americans wore a headdress. These were earned by the most powerful men of the tribe for being brave.
Native Americans hunted with bows and arrows.
Native Americans lived in wigwams. A wigwam is a round shelter covered in grass, branches, leaves, hides, and other materials.
Colonial Americans lived in colonies. A colony is a place where people from other countries came to live.
Colonial Americans were ruled by kings back in England, such as King Charles the First.
Colonial Americans wore hats to keep the sun out of their eyes. Everyone wore hats.
Colonial Americans hunted with guns called flint muskets.
Colonial Americans lived in houses made of clay. Some houses were made of wood.
Native Americans and Colonial Americans were very different!

Games are an important part of Chinese culture. This is a game called mah jong, played using tiles.

Chinese food is an important part of Chinese culture.  These are dumplings, a traditional food.
This is kung pao chicken, a dish made with chicken, peanuts, scallions, and chiles.
Martial arts are an important part of Chinese culture, also called wushu. This is a man practicing Kung fu.
There are many different fighting styles, such as Praying Mantis, Eagle Claw, and Five Animals.
Art is a part of Chinese culture. The Chinese practice many forms of art. This is a jade Buddha sculpture.
This is an example of paper cutting, another form of art. Chinese paper cutters can make very complex cuttings.
The Chinese language is a part of Chinese culture. There are many different dialects; Mandarin and Cantonese are most common.
The Chinese language is made of characters instead of letters, which can represent a whole word. It is hard to learn Chinese.

title: The Music of Johann Sebastian Bach

pages.caption: Johann Sebastian Bach was born in 1685 and lived until 1750. He was a musician and composer.
Bach played the organ. He also played the violin.
Bach wrote, or composed, many important pieces of music.
Bach liked to write music called a fugue. In a fugue, a musical idea is played by each of the instruments.
Many of Bach's works are famous, such as the Brandenburg Concertos.
The Brandenburg Concertos were written for court orchestras and are an example of Bach's instrumental music.
Bach also wrote music for choirs.
Bach worked for many years in Leipzig, Germany. He was music director at St. Thomas Church.
Here, he wrote music for the church.
When Bach was alive, his music was not well known.
Today, Johann Sebastian Bach is considered by many to be one of the greatest composers of all time.

I knew as I pulled in the parking lot today was going to be an interesting day.
To my surprise when strolling through the hallway I heard children's laughter.
As I peered into the next classroom window, I was greeted with children dressed from the past.
I noticed two women that had the same type of clothing.  What was going on?
Who were these women? Possibly substitutes for the day?  Did I forget a dress up day? I had too many questions with no answers.
I tried turning the knob but the door was locked.  I then knocked but no one seemed to hear.
I decided to return to my office for the keys. As the principal I needed to know what was going on and soon!

Rocks!
Rocks can be found everywhere.
Mountains are rock formations.
Rocks can be found in the ocean.
A person that studies rocks is called a Geologist.
Rocks come in many different shapes and sizes.
Geologists can group rocks according to their individual characteristics.
Rocks are composed of two or more minerals.
The color of a rock comes from the color of the minerals that make it up.
The shape of a rock depends on its ability to resist outside forces like wind and temperature.
There are three main groups of rock. These groups are called igneous, sedimentary, and metamorphic.
Igneous rock is formed from lava.
Lava comes from inside the Earth.
Volcanoes are formed when lava comes to the surface and erupts.
A common igneous rock is Pumice.
Pumice rocks are often used in pedicures to remove the rough dead skin from the bottoms of our feet.
Mount Rushmore National Memorial is carved from the igneous rock called Granite.
Sedimentary rock makes up most of the Earth's rocky places.
Sediment is made up of rocks, minerals, and the remains of plants and animals.
Chalk is a sedimentary rock. It is easy to see because it is white.
The remains of tiny marine animals make up chalk.
The chalk used to write on chalkboards in classrooms is man-made.
Metamorphic rock is the last of the three groups of rock.
Temperature and pressure are the conditions that make metamorphic rock.
Marble is a Metamorphic rock.
Marble is often used to make floors.
Marble floors can be found in many places like homes, churches, and museums.
Rocks can be decorative works of art.
Rocks are used in jewelry making.
People climb rocks for fun and exercise.
Rock can be used to make weapons like this arrowhead.

Every Spring we like to make Easter eggs.
We have been learning about where our food comes from.
Some food comes from plants.
Some food comes from animals.
Eggs are a food that comes from chickens.  But eggs are not always just for food.
Birds lay eggs to bring new life.  Baby birds grow in the eggs.
These eggs are not dyed.  They are robins' eggs.  Robins' eggs are blue.
After the baby bird is big enough, it hatches out of the egg. A new life is born!
In Spring, we see new life everywhere.  Flowers bloom.  Leaves grow.
We dye eggs in the colors of Spring.
The eggs help us welcome new life in the Springtime!
Why do we make Easter Eggs? Because Springtime is a time of new life.

When the phone rings, you need to answer it. Here's how:
Listen for the ring sound.
Pick it up. Hold the top by your ear and the bottom by your mouth.
Say hello. Use your voice or your iPad.
Listen to the other person say "hello." They should tell you their name.

Polar Bears by Jesse
I picked a polar bear for my mammal report.  Polar bears are the largest land carnivore and can weigh up to 1500 pounds!
Polar bears look white, but really have transparent fur and black skin.  They have large paws and black noses.
Polar bears are found in Canada, the U.S., Greenland, Russia, and Norway.
Polar bears are great swimmers!  Polar bears also move around by walking through the snow and on ice.
Polar bears mainly eat seals.  They will also eat whales and walruses.

Did you know?
Polar bears can reach 10 feet in height when standing on their legs.
Polar bears spend most of their time at sea. Scientists estimate that there are around 20000 polar bears.
Polar bears have an excellent sense of smell, with the ability to detect seals nearly a mile away.
Polar bears can reach speeds up to 25mph on land and 6mph in water.
